723971f-a.title: Manhattan: Washington Mews - University Place
723971f-a.text:
Washington Mews, at University Place, showing the east
extremity of this short thoroughfare extending one blook
west to Fifth Avenue. The small structures shown are
stcdios that were formerly stables to the residences on
Washington Square. They are a portion of the holdings of
the Sailors Snug Harbor Corp. This came into being through
the advice of Alexander Hamilton who suggested that Richard
Randall leave his estate to the activity upon which the
family fortune had sprung from.
1939-40
Alexander Alland, photo

723673f-a.title: Manhattan: University Place - Washington Mews
723673f-a.text:
University Place, north from and including Washington Mews, just
above Washington Sduare North. The office building on the S.E. corner
of 8th Street, was originally built by Merck a Company, about
1895, on the site of old 42-38 Clinton Place (now 34 East 8th Street).
On the S.E. corner of 9th Street is the Hotel Lafayette (formerly
Hotel Martin), owned by Raymond Orteig (who put up the prize which
Cha les A. Lindbergh, Jr., won by his famous solo flight in May,
1927). The new Devonshire House apartment builoing, completed in
1928 on the site of the old University Place Presbyterian Church,
is visible on the S.W. corner of 10th Street.
March 25, 1933.
P. L. Sperr.  73c w 57S
